# Chapter 5 — Recursion + tail calls

Scheme has no `for` loop; it has recursion. The interpreter uses a trampoline so tail-recursive calls run in constant stack. The chapter env preloads `count-down` and `sum-to` so you can call them right away.

## The count-down helper is already loaded

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(count-down 5)
</pre>

## Sum to N — tail-recursive

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(sum-to 10)
</pre>

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(sum-to 1000)
</pre>

## Write your own — factorial

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define (fact n)
  (if (= n 0) 1 (* n (fact (- n 1)))))
(fact 10)
</pre>

## The trampoline

<pre data-runnable data-lang=\"sakura-scheme\">
(define (loop n)
  (if (= n 0) 'done (loop (- n 1))))
(loop 50000)
</pre>

> **Sakura says**
>
> `(loop (- n 1))` at the tail position is why 50,000 doesn't blow the stack. The interpreter turns the call into a jump. Chapter 5's `,help` on `evaluate` shows this — it's the fuel-budgeted trampoline that carries every Scheme program I run.

> **Under the hood**
>
> Every call in tail position (last thing your function does) reuses the current stack frame instead of adding to it. The evaluator inspects the AST and picks the trampoline arm for calls it can recognise. Non-tail calls fall back to a normal recursive `evaluate`.

